full_text:

b"@JamesMolloyVA Well, they're a teen, so they're not going to be able to make any active decisions for 5 years anyway.

If anything happens, it'd be puberty blockers, and they're proven reversible anyway.

Just get them seeing a gender therapist, and take those steps to learn together as a fam."

b'@JamesMolloyVA Everyone starts off uneducated about it though, lmao. Help and guide, but don't assume it's a phase, as you have no idea.

Hell, I hated gay people because I didn't want to admit that, "yo, maybe I don't mind dick so much".

When you're a teen, it's fucking confusing.'

full_text:
@JamesMolloyVA Also, you have no idea what's going on inside someone's head, and it's impossible to paint all people with the same brush.

b"@VoMylo @jeffreynbaker 2 seconds onto the website, and I'm prompted to hire a voice actress for \xc2\xa312 for 150 lines for a professional commercial, with only \xc2\xa340 for the commercial rights.

Via an agency, the same job would be valued in thousands.

How do you not see the industry issue with the site?"

b"@KenMarsigliaVo I look forward to seeing how you feel about it in a couple of months.

Initial success may seem great (I've been there), but I've seen enough of the horror stories that I am genuinely concerned for you and others on the site. 

Best of luck with it all though, I need to sleep. \xf0\x9f\x92\xa4"

full_text:
@KenMarsigliaVo But your agent is getting you commercial/industry gigs where the 80% goes a lot further.

20% of $5 burns a lot quicker than 20% of $5,000.

@jeffreynbaker That's what was first assumed, but that's how the standard rates for VA has been reduced overall.

Normalisation of those Fiverr rates led to lower pay for commercial and professional work, and it's by people saying "fuck that" and blacklisting which has brought it back up again.
full_text(utf-8): b'@jeffreynbaker That\'s what was first assumed, but that\'s how the standard rates for VA has been reduced overall.\n\nNormalisation of those Fiverr rates led to lower pay for commercial and professional work, and it\'s by people saying "fuck that" and blacklisting which has brought it back up again.'

b'@jeffreynbaker One could argue, "that's the nature of the industry", but why is it?

Would we expect plumbers to be paid below minimum wage for 5-7 years before saying, "alright, you've earned minimum wage now, congrats!"

It's genuinely the sweatshop of voice work, and it's scarily normalised.'

full_text:
@HanaMaeVoice Some of the complaints I've heard about people hiring them through the site has been wild, so I'm not surprised, unfortunately.

I'd honestly say it's not worth doing, because it'll take years to get to a point of earning decently to make the headache worthwhile.
full_text(utf-8): b"@HanaMaeVoice Some of the complaints I've heard about people hiring them through the site has been wild, so I'm not surprised, unfortunately.\n\nI'd honestly say it's not worth doing, because it'll take years to get to a point of earning decently to make the headache worthwhile."

b"@jeffreynbaker Honestly, yes.

Anyone who touts 'millionaire through fiverr' stuff, either got in very early, or allowed some rough exploitation of their craft for 5-7 years straight.

I've spent a lot of time studying the platform, and there's thousands exploited for every one success story."

b"@jeffreynbaker Same applies for politics, personal views, and even minor slights.

Blacklisting, by nature, is annoyingly subjective, but usually done in order to protect.

With Fiverr in particular, it's just a bad look for voice actors, whilst devaluing our work, so I can see why it happens."

full_text:
@jeffreynbaker The issue with blacklisting is you won't know you've been hit until it's happened. You could go your entire career without knowing, questioning why you're not getting hired.

I personally know some people who avoid Fiverr people at all costs, but there's no checklist or anything.

full_text: Those who gain the role within the server are those who now represent VAC, and their words will have that weight behind them. Responsibility is key in a world with mass-misinformation. This is not something we take lightly, nor should others in the community.

full_text: If you lie, it will be discovered. If you say, "well, I'm part of x agency or x talent list", we will have friends within the same networks who will know if you're lying through your teeth, and that will reflect on your application, giving us a lot of mistrust in the rest.
full_text(utf-8): b'If you lie, it will be discovered. If you say, "well, I\'m part of x agency or x talent list", we will have friends within the same networks who will know if you\'re lying through your teeth, and that will reflect on your application, giving us a lot of mistrust in the rest.'

full_text: Simple background checks can be very revealing. Social media is a reflection of the self and level of professionalism. So, if it takes us seconds to discover you dropping slurs on Twitter, you're not going to be accepted. It's really that simple.
full_text(utf-8): b"Simple background checks can be very revealing. Social media is a reflection of the self and level of professionalism. So, if it takes us seconds to discover you dropping slurs on Twitter, you're not going to be accepted. It's really that simple."

However, there are a few things points, which I'd like to discuss below;

Your casting always needs to encompass your message, and it's always telling when a project doesn't care enough to consider it.

b"@StarryFlame @tha_rami Context matters, as does the role.

Is the role a Latinx kid living in a Latinx family, living the Latinx experience? I'd turn her down immediately.

Does the character have one line, and then disappear entirely? Then *maybe* I'd cast her, if I don't have a Latinx voice handy."

full_text:
@StarryFlame @tha_rami Voice acting is more than 'just a voice', you could be representing the hopes, dreams and aspirations for children and millions everywhere.

Thus, more responsibility is needed with casting, otherwise it's just lazy, pathetic and frustrating.
full_text(utf-8): b"@StarryFlame @tha_rami Voice acting is more than 'just a voice', you could be representing the hopes, dreams and aspirations for children and millions everywhere.\n\nThus, more responsibility is needed with casting, otherwise it's just lazy, pathetic and frustrating."

b"@StarryFlame @tha_rami If you have an open mind, then hear me out for two seconds.

It does matter. 

If you were a child, and learned the character you saw as *you* on television was voiced by someone who doesn't look like you, wouldn't that child suddenly feel disillusioned and heartbroken?"

full_text:
@StarryFlame @tha_rami Where do you think a voice comes from? An amorphous blob without form, humanity or lived experience?

It's lazy casting to just accept whatever voice throws itself at you. If representative casting is a 'red flag', you're gonna be very surprised if you audition for pro work.
full_text(utf-8): b"@StarryFlame @tha_rami Where do you think a voice comes from? Cool. Thanks for your opinion.

Adam Ruins Everything did a wonderful little piece on how the American funeral system is designed to sap as much money from people during their grieving process as possible, with it not being that dissimilar in the UK (bar the 'open casket' ceremony).

https://t.co/ke1GXHRQhH

full_text:
"why talk about money?", "shouldn't you be grieving?"

I have been grieving, and I still am. But, I want to also acknowledge that the system is broken, and a funeral shouldn't need to be a massively pay-walled privilege (please research 'pauper funerals').

full_text:
In spite of this, nothing could prepare us for the crazy amount we paid. 

Most baffling being;
¬£600 for a coffin that was only seen for 10 minutes, and cremated along with my grandmother.
¬£2,000 for a room we used for 20 minutes.
Plus, a good 20 other charges in the ¬£100 range.

full_text:
My family is a sensible one, and even in times of tragedy, we like to remain practical and level-headed.

Acknowledging the purpose of cremation, we kept things as low-key and cost-effective as possible, with the intent of getting a headstone and burying at a later date.
